===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|thries}}, from earlier {{m|enm|thrie}} (from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|þrīġa}}) + adverbial {{term|-s}}. Cognate with Saterland Frisian {{m|stq|träie||thrice}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/θraɪs/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-thrice.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|aɪs|lang=en}}

===Adverb===
{{en-adv|-}}

# [[three]] [[time]]s

====Usage notes====
* Unlike {{m|en|once}} and {{m|en|twice}}, ''thrice'' is somewhat dated in American and British usage, sometimes used for a comical or intentionally archaic effect. {{m|en|[[three|Three]] [[times]]}} is the more standard and typical usage. On the other hand, ''once'' and ''twice'' are almost always preferred over {{m|en|[[one]] [[time]]}} and {{m|en|[[two]] [[times]]}} respectively. ''Thrice'' does however retain some currency in compounds like {{m|en|thrice-monthly}}, and it is still standard and stylistically neutral in [[Indian English]].

